This is about a machine. A device. Not a person. So let's be clear.

### Printing Press

A [printing press](/Printing) is a mechanical contraption, designed for the sole purpose of applying ink to a medium. Think paper, or cloth. It’s a crude, yet effective, way to transfer information. Before this marvel, people would rub, brush, and generally abuse their chosen material until the ink, somehow, decided to stick. This press, however, accelerated the process. Dramatically. It was primarily used for texts, but its invention and subsequent global dissemination was, and I quote, "one of the most influential events in the second millennium." Flattering, I suppose.

#### Gutenberg's Little Machine

In the year of our Lord 1440, in the land of [Germany](/Germany), a [goldsmith](/Goldsmith) named [Johannes Gutenberg](/Johannes_Gutenberg) decided to bless the world with the [movable-type](/Movable_type) printing press. This, apparently, kicked off the "[Printing Revolution](/Printing_Revolution)". It was modeled after existing [screw presses](/Screw_press), the kind you might see crushing grapes for wine. A single one of these Renaissance contraptions could churn out up to 3,600 pages a day. For perspective, hand-printing managed a mere forty, and hand-copying, well, that was for [scribes](/Scribe) who had too much time and not enough ambition. Gutenberg's genius lay in his [hand mould](/Hand_mould), which allowed for the rapid and precise creation of metal [movable type](/Movable_type). These two innovations, the mould and the press itself, slashed the cost of books in Europe, especially for those shorter print runs.

#### The Spread of Ink

From its humble beginnings in [Mainz](/Mainz), the movable-type printing press decided to go on a world tour, or at least a European one. Within decades, it had set up shop in over 200 cities across a dozen countries. By the turn of the 16th century, [Western Europe](/Western_Europe) was drowning in printed matter—over 20 million volumes. And it didn't stop there. The next century saw that number multiply tenfold, reaching an estimated 150 to 200 million copies. The [Western Hemisphere](/Western_Hemisphere) got its first taste in 1539, courtesy of the Spaniards in [New Spain](/New_Spain). The British colonies in [America](/United_States) eventually caught up, driven by an insatiable demand for [Bibles](/Bible) and other religious tracts. The act of operating a press became so synonymous with the enterprise that it lent its name to a whole new medium: "[the press](/Newspaper)". Charming.

#### A Societal Shift

This mechanical movable-type printing thing, it truly ushered in the age of [mass communication](/Mass_communication). It irrevocably altered the fabric of society. Information and ideas, now able to flow with relative freedom across borders, bypassed the usual gatekeepers. The [Reformation](/Reformation) gained traction, and the established powers, both political and religious, started to feel the heat. Literacy rates, predictably, shot up, chipping away at the monopoly the educated elite held on knowledge. The burgeoning [middle class](/Middle_class) benefited, and a sense of cultural self-awareness bloomed across Europe, fueling the rise of [nationalism](/Nationalism) and solidifying the status of [vernacular](/Vernaculars) languages, much to the detriment of [Latin](/Latin)'s reign as the *lingua franca*. By the 19th century, the hand-cranked Gutenberg-style press was out, replaced by steam-powered [rotary presses](/Rotary_press) that could print on an industrial scale. The world, it seems, just kept getting louder.

### History

#### Economic and Intellectual Currents

The late medieval period in Europe was a hotbed of economic and socio-cultural change. This created fertile ground for Gutenberg's printing press. The entrepreneurial spirit of [emerging capitalism](/History_of_capitalism) was already nudging traditional production methods towards greater efficiency. Meanwhile, the rise of [medieval learning](/Medieval_university) and an increasingly literate [middle class](/Middle_class) meant a sky-high demand for books, a demand that the snail's pace of hand-copying simply couldn't meet.

#### Technological Precursors

Before Gutenberg, several key technologies were brewing: the manufacturing of [paper](/Papermaking), the development of [ink](/Ink), the ancient art of [woodblock printing](/Woodblock_printing), and the invention of [eyeglasses](/Eyeglasses). These, combined with a mature understanding of various [medieval technologies](/Medieval_technology), provided the building blocks. Gutenberg, in his infinite wisdom, gathered these disparate elements, fused them into a coherent system, and then improved upon them with his own ingenious inventions.

*   **The Screw Press:** This ancient Roman technology, dating back to the first century AD, was already a workhorse. Used for crushing grapes for wine and olives for oil, it was a staple in the [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean_cuisine) and [medieval diet](/Medieval_cuisine). By Gutenberg's time, it was also employed in urban settings for pressing cloth patterns. It's believed Gutenberg drew inspiration from these, and perhaps even the paper presses that had begun appearing in [German lands](/Holy_Roman_Empire) by the late 14th century.

*   **Islamic Innovations:** During the [Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age), Arab Muslims were already printing texts, including passages from the [Qur’an](/Qur%E2%80%99an), using paper made through a process they’d refined from Chinese techniques. This significantly boosted manuscript production. In [Egypt](/Egypt), during the [Fatimid](/Fatimid) period, texts were reproduced on paper strips by hand, with multiple copies supplied to meet demand.

Gutenberg essentially took the screw press's basic design and mechanized printing. However, printing placed different demands on the machine. He adapted it to apply pressure evenly and with the necessary elasticity. To speed things up, he added a movable undertable for swift sheet changes.

*   **Movable Type:** The concept of movable type wasn't entirely new. Evidence suggests the [typographical principle](/Typographical_principle)—reusing individual characters to form text—was known in Europe from at least the 12th century, possibly earlier, with the oldest known application being the [Phaistos disc](/Phaistos_disc).

    The first true movable type was invented in 11th-century China by [Bi Sheng](/Bi_Sheng), using baked clay. Later, in Korea during the [Goryeo](/Goryeo) era, the [Jikji] book, printed in 1377, is the oldest known book printed with [metal movable type](/Type_case). Other examples, like the [Prüfening inscription](/Pr%C3%BCfening_dedicatory_inscription) in Germany and [letter tiles](/Letter_tiles) from England, show early attempts. However, these techniques lacked the refinement and efficiency for widespread adoption. Some scholars suggest that movable-type printing in China and Korea saw limited use compared to woodblock printing.

    Gutenberg, a goldsmith by trade, revolutionized the process by separating typesetting and printing. He created his type pieces from a [lead](/Lead)-based [alloy](/Alloy) that proved ideal for printing and is still used today. His crucial invention was a [hand mould](/Hand_mould) and [matrix](/Matrix_(printing)) system that allowed for the mass production of uniform metal letters. The [Latin alphabet](/Latin_alphabet), with its relatively small number of characters compared to [logographic writing systems](/Logogram), was a significant advantage, requiring only about two dozen basic letters.

*   **The Codex:** The book format itself, the [codex](/Codex), which had replaced the ancient [scroll](/Scroll) by the early Middle Ages, was another crucial factor. Originating in the [Roman period](/Roman_Empire), the codex was more compact, easier to read by turning pages, and allowed for writing on both sides, unlike the scroll.

*   **Paper Production:** Medieval papermakers had already begun mechanizing production with water-powered [paper mills](/Paper_mill). This dramatically increased output and lowered costs, making paper a viable alternative to expensive [parchment](/Parchment). By the late 13th century, paper production centers were multiplying in [Italy](/Italy), eventually reaching Germany a century later.

Despite the advancements in paper, parchment still held its ground, even appearing in Gutenberg's famous [42-line Bible](/42-line_Bible). Gutenberg also had to conquer the challenge of ink. Traditional water-based inks soaked the paper, so he developed an oil-based ink that was suitable for high-quality printing with metal type.

#### Function and Mechanics

The classical printing press was a substantial piece of machinery, typically standing 5 to 7 feet long, 3 feet wide, and 7 feet tall. The process began with a compositor arranging small metal letters, known as type, into lines of text. These lines were then grouped into pages and locked into a wooden frame called a [forme](/Forme_(printing)). This forme was placed onto a flat stone bed, often referred to as the "coffin."

Ink was applied using two [ink balls](/Ink_ball)—pads made of poreless dog skin, stuffed with sheep's wool. These were dabbed onto the inked type. A damp sheet of paper, dampness aiding ink transfer, was then carefully positioned on a tympan. Pins held it in place. The paper, now sandwiched between a [frisket](/Frisket) and the [tympan](/Tympan) (frames designed to protect the paper from unwanted ink), was folded down onto the inked type.

The stone bed carrying the forme was then rolled under the [platen](/Platen)—a flat surface that would press the paper against the type. This was achieved using a [windlass](/Windlass) mechanism operated by a handle called the 'rounce'. The impression was made by turning a long lever, the "bar" or "'Devil's Tail'", which rotated a screw, forcing the platen down. In a well-functioning press, the elasticity of the paper and frisket would then spring the bar back, raising the platen. The bed was rolled back, the tympan and frisket lifted, and the printed sheet removed. These presses were entirely hand-operated. After 1800, iron presses emerged, some capable of being powered by [steam](/Steam_power).

William Skeen, in 1872, described the press's operation:

> This sketch represents a press in its completed form, with tympans attached to the end of the carriage, and with the frisket above the tympans. The tympans, inner and outer, are thin iron frames, one fitting into the other, on each of which is stretched a skin of parchment or a breadth of fine cloth. A woollen blanket or two with a few sheets of paper are placed between these, the whole thus forming a thin elastic pad, on which the sheet to be printed is laid. The frisket is a slender frame-work, covered with coarse paper, on which an impression is first taken; the whole of the printed part is then cut out, leaving apertures exactly corresponding with the pages of type on the carriage of the press. The frisket when folded on to the tympans, and both turned down over the forme of types and run in under the platten, preserves the sheet from contact with any thing but the inked surface of the types, when the pull, which brings down the screw and forces the platten to produce the impression, is made by the pressman who works the lever,—to whom is facetiously given the title of "the practitioner at the bar."

#### Gutenberg's Masterpiece

Johannes Gutenberg's work on the printing press began around 1436. He collaborated with Andreas Dritzehn, a man skilled in [gem-cutting](/Lapidary), and Andreas Heilmann, a paper mill owner. The earliest official record of his work comes from a 1439 lawsuit, where witness testimonies mentioned Gutenberg's types, an inventory of metals, and his type molds.

Drawing on his background as a professional goldsmith, Gutenberg expertly utilized his knowledge of metals. He pioneered the use of a [lead](/Lead)-[tin](/Tin)-[antimony](/Antimony) alloy for his type, which was crucial for creating durable, high-quality print. His most ingenious invention, the [matrix](/Matrix_(printing)), allowed for the rapid and precise molding of uniform type blocks. His [type case](/Type_case) likely held around 290 separate compartments for letters, special characters, [ligatures](/Typographic_ligature), and [punctuation marks](/Punctuation_marks).

Gutenberg also developed an oil-based [ink](/Ink), more durable than the water-based inks previously used. He printed on both paper and [vellum](/Vellum). While his famous [Gutenberg Bible](/Gutenberg_Bible) featured only some limited color printing for headings, a later work, the [Mainz Psalter](/Mainz_Psalter) of 1453 (published by his successors [Johann Fust](/Johann_Fust) and [Peter Schöffer](/Peter_Sch%C3%B6ffer)), showcased elaborate red and blue printed initials.

#### The Printing Revolution Unleashed

The "[printing revolution](/Printing_revolution)" wasn't just about a machine; it was about the explosion of information and ideas it enabled. The printing press became an "agent of change," fundamentally reshaping societies. The initial surge in printing was driven largely by the demand for religious texts, like the [Bible](/Bible). Later, printed materials—newspapers, pamphlets, bulletins—became powerful tools in shaping public opinion, influencing events like the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War) and the [American](/American_Revolution) and [French Revolutions](/French_Revolution). Of course, with this newfound power came the inevitable discussions around censorship and freedom of the press.

##### Mass Production and Dissemination

European book output experienced a meteoric rise, from a few million to an estimated one billion copies in less than four centuries. The invention of mechanical movable type printing triggered a rapid expansion across Europe. Within decades, printing had spread from a single shop in [Mainz](/Mainz) to over 270 cities. By 1480, printers were active in 110 locations across Europe, and by 1500, the printed book was a ubiquitous presence.

Italy, a hub of early printing, saw shops in 77 cities by 1500. By the end of the century, printing had reached 151 Italian locations, with nearly three thousand printers documented. However, printing centers soon consolidated, with one-third of Italian printers operating in [Venice](/Venice).

By 1500, Western Europe had produced over twenty million volumes. The following century witnessed a tenfold increase, to an estimated 150 to 200 million copies. Presses around 1600 could produce 1,500 to 3,600 impressions daily, a stark contrast to the manual rubbing methods used in the [Far East](/Far_Eastern), which barely reached forty pages a day.

The works of [Erasmus](/Erasmus) alone sold over 750,000 copies during his lifetime. During the early days of the Reformation, the revolutionary potential of mass printing caught both princes and the [papacy](/Papacy) off guard. Between 1518 and 1524, book publications in Germany alone increased sevenfold. Martin Luther's tracts were distributed in 300,000 copies between 1518 and 1520. The speed and affordability of printed texts also paved the way for the first [newspapers](/Newspaper), opening new avenues for disseminating current information. Surviving pre-16th century printed works, known as [incunabula](/Incunabula), are now prized by libraries in Europe and [North America](/North_America).

##### Circulation of Ideas

The printing press fostered a [community of scientists](/Scientists) who could readily share their discoveries through widely distributed scholarly journals, a key factor in the [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution). It also redefined [authorship](/Author), making it more significant and profitable. Precise citation became possible, establishing the principle of "One Author, one work (title), one piece of information." Before printing, the author's identity was often less critical, as copies of works like those by [Aristotle](/Aristotle) varied significantly depending on where they were produced. Many works from before the printing press have even lost their author's name entirely.

The standardization of information facilitated by printing led to the widespread adoption of page numbering, [tables of contents](/Table_of_contents), and [indices](/Index_(publishing)). The very act of reading transformed, shifting from oral recitations to silent, private engagement. Over the next two centuries, the increased availability of printed materials dramatically boosted adult literacy rates across Europe.

The printing press was a significant step towards the [democratization of knowledge](/Democratization_of_knowledge). Within 50 to 60 years, the entire [classical canon](/Classics) had been reprinted and disseminated throughout Europe. More individuals gained access to both new and old knowledge, fostering wider discussion. Book production became more commercialized, leading to the introduction of [copyright](/Copyright) laws. However, the press also faced criticism for its potential to spread misinformation.

The popularization of knowledge also led to the decline of Latin as the primary scholarly language, replaced by [vernaculars](/Vernaculars), thereby increasing the diversity of published works. Simultaneously, printing helped standardize the spelling and syntax of these vernaculars, contributing to the rise of [nationalism](/Nationalism).

Economically, the printing press fueled city growth. The publication of trade manuals and instructional books, such as those on [double-entry bookkeeping](/Double-entry_bookkeeping), improved trade reliability, weakened merchant guilds, and empowered individual traders.

#### Industrial Printing Presses

At the dawn of the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), the fundamental mechanics of the Gutenberg-style press remained largely unchanged, though incremental improvements in materials and design had boosted efficiency. By 1800, [Lord Stanhope](/Charles_Stanhope,_3rd_Earl_Stanhope) introduced a press made entirely of [cast iron](/Cast_iron). This design reduced the required force by 90% and doubled the printing area, achieving a capacity of 480 pages per hour—twice that of the older models. Still, the limitations of the traditional method were becoming apparent.

Two key innovations radically transformed the printing press: the integration of steam power and the replacement of the flatbed with the rotary motion of cylinders. German printer [Friedrich Koenig](/Friedrich_Koenig) successfully combined these elements in his press designs between 1802 and 1818. Moving to London in 1804, Koenig partnered with [Thomas Bensley](/Thomas_Bensley), securing financial backing in 1807. His 1810 patent described a steam press that was essentially a hand press connected to a [steam engine](/Steam_engine). With the assistance of fellow German engineer [Andreas Friedrich Bauer](/Andreas_Friedrich_Bauer), Koenig tested his first production model in April 1811.

In 1814, Koenig and Bauer supplied two of their presses to [The Times](/The_Times) in [London](/London). These machines could produce 1,100 impressions per hour, revolutionizing newspaper production. Subsequent improvements allowed printing on both sides of a sheet simultaneously. This marked the beginning of mass-produced newspapers, significantly contributing to the spread of literacy. From the 1820s onwards, this transformation also impacted [book](/Book) production, necessitating greater standardization in titles and other [metadata](/Metadata_(computing)). Koenig & Bauer AG, their company, remains a major manufacturer of printing presses today.

##### The Rotary Press

The steam-powered [rotary printing press](/Rotary_printing_press), invented in the [United States](/United_States) in 1843 by [Richard M. Hoe](/Richard_M._Hoe), eventually enabled the production of millions of pages daily. Mass printing flourished with the adoption of rolled paper, allowing for continuous feed and significantly faster press speeds. Hoe's initial design operated at 2,000 revolutions per hour, printing four page images per revolution, resulting in a throughput of 8,000 pages per hour. By 1891, newspapers like The [New York World](/New_York_World) and the Philadelphia Item were using presses that could produce 90,000 four-page sheets or 48,000 eight-page sheets per hour.

The mid-19th century also saw the development of [jobbing presses](/Jobbing_presses). These smaller, versatile presses were designed for printing small items like [billheads](/Billhead), letterheads, business cards, and envelopes. Jobbing presses allowed for quick setup and production, with setup times for small jobs averaging under 15 minutes. Even treadle-powered models could achieve 1,000 impressions per hour, with speeds of 1,500 often reached for simple tasks like envelope printing. This made job printing a cost-effective duplication solution for businesses.

