4.  Korean printing methods, specifically, are noted for nearly doubling printing speed and producing over 40 copies a day, representing a peak in that technology.
5.  The spread of printing across Europe was rapid, with presses established in numerous cities by the end of the 15th century and an estimated 20 million volumes produced by 1500. Output increased significantly in the following century.
6.  The first printing press in the Western Hemisphere was established in New Spain in 1539.
7.  The arrival of printing presses in British colonial America was driven by demand for religious literature.
8.  The term "the press" evolved to signify the entire enterprise of publishing and mass communication.
9.  The impact of printing on society included the spread of information, the Reformation, increased literacy, the rise of the middle class, proto-nationalism, and the shift away from Latin.
10. The transition to steam-powered rotary presses in the 19th century enabled industrial-scale printing.

